Exploring a dataframe.

This is your cheatsheet for the question, what does this dataframe actually contain? Spark gives you a small toolkit for inspecting one.

Count returns the number of rows — but notice that it is an action, so it triggers a real job on the cluster. Columns hands you the column names as a plain Python list. Dtypes gives you a list of name and type pairs. Schema returns the full struct type object, and print schema pretty-prints that same thing in a readable tree.

For the data itself, describe gives you count, mean, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum across the numeric columns. Summary does everything describe does and adds the quartiles on top.

And then there is show, which prints the actual rows. One tip worth remembering: pass truncate equals false, and Spark stops cutting off long values so you see the full content of each cell.
